<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="bf87c14c-7a59-5279-841d-fdebba05b4e5" activityNameId="7feac7e5-b390-4bdb-9d3e-b5f16391eead" parentActivityId="e7dfda62-0a65-568f-94e7-f4f8bc12ed89" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">phenolic resin production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">naphthalene-2,7-diol</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">phenol</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Formaldehyde polymer with 2,7-naphthalenediol and phenol (9CI)</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Formaldehyde</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">1-(beta-Bromophenethyl)piperidine hydrobromide</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">L 8</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">L 8 (phenolic resin)</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">26936-19-6</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with the production of phenolic resin. The dataset includes raw materials and chemicals used for production, estimated emissions to air and water from production (incomplete) as well as the estimated energy demand and infrastructure of the plant (approximation). Solid wastes are omitted.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of pure phenolic resin. Phenolic resins are polycondensation products of phenols and aldehydes, in particular phenol and formaldehyde. Within the phenolic resins, two different types can be distinguished: </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">- Novolacs: Polycondesation is not stopped but brought to completion. The characteristic functional group here is just the alkylidene bridge – there are no other functional groups. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">- Resols: Synthesized by base-catalyzed polycondensation, stopped before completion. The characteristic functional groups therefore are the hydroxymethyl group and the dimethylene ether bridge.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Depending on the type of phenolic resin (and if they are cross-linked or not), a huge variety of different applications are possible. One of the first was the use as varnishes (usually unlinked novolacs). Nowadays a lot of further applications, not only from the construction sector,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">have been identified – e.g. in the sector of printing technology, in the production of epoxy resins, as adhesives in a variety of cases, etc.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">The data is based on estimations as well as approximations based on data from a large chemical factory (Gendorf 2016).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. ecoinvent report No. 8, v2.0. EMPA Dübendorf, Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="4a11cbd4-74bf-47fb-9fe5-6e97e3db136b">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2013:Manufacture of plastics and synthetic rubber in primary forms</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The data used has no specific geographical origin as it is based on stoechiometric calculations and estimations. It is assumed to be representative of the production processes in this geography. Some values are based on data from a large chemical factory located in Germany. These are assumed to be valid for this geography.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Production from phenol and formaldehyde (as examples of the respective substance classes) with a yield of 98%. The inventory is based on stoechiometric calculations. The emissions to air (0.2 wt% of raw material input) and water were estimated using mass balance. Treatment of the wastewater in an internal wastewater treatment plant is assumed (elimination efficiency of 90% for C).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. ecoinvent report No. 8, v2.0. EMPA Dübendorf, Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2000-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Date of published literature. Some values are based on data published by the Gendorf factory that were collected between 2011 and 2015. The time period has been adjusted accordingly. For more details, see the comments of the exchanges.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="19d552c5-e865-5438-96b4-0730024f2a03" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="RP" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="0d84cdfe-bcf2-4821-8f34-d93b9f611c11" productionVolumeAmount="4652183908.04598" productionVolumeVariableName="RP_PV">
        <name xml:lang="en">phenolic resin</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Phenolic resins are polycondensation products of phenols and aldehydes, in particular phenol and formaldehyde. Within the phenolic resins, two different types can be distinguished: 
- Novolacs: Polycondesation is not stopped but brought to completion. The characteristic functional group here is just the alkylidene bridge – there are no other functional groups. 
- Resols: Synthesized by base-catalyzed polycondensation, stopped before completion. The characteristic functional groups therefore are the hydroxymethyl group and the dimethylene ether bridge.
Depending on the type of phenolic resin (and if they are cross-linked or not), a huge variety of different applications are possible. One of the first was the use as varnishes (usually unlinked novolacs). Nowadays a lot of further applications, not only from the construction sector,
have been identified – e.g. in the sector of printing technology, in the production of epoxy resins, as adhesives in a variety of cases, etc.

References:
Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. ecoinvent report No. 8, v2.0. EMPA Dübendorf, Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</comment>
